    </div>

    <!-- THE SCIENCE OF SOUR -->
    <h2>What Makes Gummies Sour — The Science Behind the Pucker</h2>

    <p>Understanding how sourness works helps explain why some sour gummies deliver an intense face-puckering hit while others offer a gentle tang. The sour sensation is created entirely by food-grade acids, and each acid produces a distinct flavor profile and duration. The three primary acids used in sour candy are citric acid, malic acid, and tartaric acid — and the best sour gummies use strategic combinations of all three.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="star" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Citric Acid</h4>
        <p>Derived from citrus fruits. Produces a sharp, immediate sourness that hits fast and fades quickly. The most common acid in sour candy coatings. pH level: 2.2 in pure solution.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="leaf" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Malic Acid</h4>
        <p>Found naturally in apples and grapes. Creates a smoother, longer-lasting sourness that builds gradually. Often mixed into the gummy base itself for sustained tartness throughout chewing.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="target" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Tartaric Acid</h4>
        <p>Extracted from grape fermentation. Provides a deeper, wine-like tartness. Used by Sour Patch Kids and premium brands to add complexity beyond simple citric sourness.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="scale" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Fumaric Acid</h4>
        <p>The most stable of the food acids, with the longest shelf life. Releases slowly for a sustained sour experience. Used in Trolli products and extreme sour candies.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>The best sour gummies layer multiple acids: a citric acid coating for the initial punch, malic acid in the gummy base for sustained sourness, and tartaric or fumaric acid for depth and complexity. Cheaper brands rely on citric acid alone, which creates a one-dimensional sour-then-sweet experience. This acid layering is the primary differentiator between a mediocre sour gummy and an exceptional one.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <div class="tip-box-ico">i</div>
      <p><strong>Dental tip:</strong> The citric acid in sour gummy coatings has a pH of approximately 2.5 — well below the 5.5 threshold that begins dissolving tooth enamel. The American Dental Association recommends rinsing your mouth with water immediately after eating sour candy and waiting at least 30 minutes before brushing to avoid spreading acid across softened enamel.</p>
    </div>

