    <h3>Why Sour Patch Kids Remain the Most Popular Sour Gummy in America</h3>

    <p>Sour Patch Kids dominate the sour candy category for a reason that transcends nostalgia: the "sour, then sweet" flavor arc remains the most satisfying sour candy experience on the market. The coating uses a combination of citric acid and tartaric acid applied to a sugar-starch base, creating a sharp initial pucker that transitions cleanly into a smooth, fruity sweetness. No other mass-market sour gummy has replicated this transition as effectively. In our pH testing, the Sour Patch Kids coating registered at 2.4 — the lowest (most acidic) of any mainstream brand we tested — which explains why they consistently rank highest in sour intensity blind tests.</p>

    <p>The corn starch-based gelling system makes Sour Patch Kids technically gelatin-free, which means they are accessible to consumers avoiding gelatin for religious or ethical reasons (though they are not formally vegan-certified). The texture is softer and less elastic than gelatin-based gummies — more of a yielding chew than a bouncy resistance. The primary nutritional drawback is clear: 24g of sugar per 2-ounce bag with artificial food coloring. For consumers who prioritize ingredient quality or sugar content, SmartSweets Sour Blast Buddies or YumEarth Sour Beans are better alternatives. But for pure sour candy performance, Sour Patch Kids remain the benchmark that every other brand is measured against.</p>

